Introduction¶

"Nexa University" strives to be globally recognized for academic brilliance in the center of a big city. To do this, the university board strives to comprehend the elements that influence worldwide university rankings. Rather than just looking at metrics, they want to know what makes a university genuinely remarkable. Is it research, faculty excellence, alumni success, or a combination of the three?

They enlist the help of data scientist Patrick Chaccour to solve the riddle. Their objective is to examine massive datasets from numerous rating agencies, each with their own set of criteria. The goal is to discover the spirit of top-ranked schools rather than just integrate data.

Data Integration: Parallel Computing¶

Using DASK¶

1) Convert main dataframe to Dask dataframes 2) Merge Datasets using Dask 3) Reconvert to pd

In [21]:
df_uni_ranking_dd = dd.from_pandas(df_uni_ranking, npartitions=cpu_count())
df_skl_ct_dd = dd.from_pandas(df_skl_ct, npartitions=cpu_count())
df_shanghai_rankings_dd = dd.from_pandas(df_shanghai_rankings, npartitions=cpu_count())
df_times_ranking_dd = dd.from_pandas(df_times_ranking, npartitions=cpu_count())
In [22]:
def dask_merge():
    data_dask = df_uni_ranking_dd.merge(df_skl_ct_dd, left_on='institution', 
                                        right_on='school_name', how='left')
    
    data_dask = data_dask.merge(df_shanghai_rankings_dd, left_on=['institution', 'year'], 
                                right_on=['university_name', 'year'], how='left', suffixes=('', '_shanghai'))
    
    data_dask = data_dask.merge(df_times_ranking_dd, left_on=['institution', 'year'], 
                                right_on=['university_name', 'year'], how='left', suffixes=('', '_times'))
    
    return data_dask
In [23]:
merged_data_dask = dask_merge()

# Convert the Dask dataframe back to a Pandas dataframe

Step 7: Documentation¶

Objective:¶

The goal was to analyze the data from several ranking agencies to better understand the elements that influence global university rankings.

Methodology:¶

  • Data Cleaning: Depending on the relevance of the missing data, missing values were imputed or rows were eliminated.
  • Data Merging: The integration was carried out using the university's name and year.
  • EDA: We dug into the datasets to look for patterns, distributions, and correlations between measurements.

Key Findings:¶

  • Distribution of Universities: The United States has the most universities in the datasets, followed by the United Kingdom, Canada, and Japan.
  • World Rankings: According to the df_uni_ranking dataset, a substantial number of universities have rankings ranging from 400 to 1000.
  • Teaching Quality and Publishing Rankings: There is a positive association between teaching quality and publication rankings

Utilization of Technologies:¶

The following tools were used:

  • Pandas
  • Matplotlib
  • Dask
  • Spark

Data Integration Strategies:¶

  • Schema Mapping: Identifying matched columns.
  • Data Transformation: Maintaining consistentancy.
  • Manual Data Reconciliation: Merging datasets.

Results:¶

The combined dataset provides a full perspective of university rankings, allowing for cross-comparison and more in-depth analysis.

Conclusion¶

By studying top-ranked universities, "Nexa University" strives for global academic excellence. Patrick Chaccour, a data scientist, assisted in navigating large datasets from rating organizations in order to comprehend institution reputation beyond measurements. We discovered that the prestige of colleges, such as Harvard, is influenced by a variety of criteria, including research, faculty excellence, alumni achievement, international diversity... The purpose of "Nexa University" is to take a comprehensive approach that blends diversified skills, research, and real-world preparation. The road to global recognition is difficult, but it is doable with the right strategy.
